/PGMAòARIV/XX128/XX/PR

/ITIt is customary to acknowledge mourners on the Shabbat during shivah, traditionally their
first return to the synagogue following the death of their loved one. They are welcomed with
the words:/PR

/HY/PR

ַ/ָוֺם ְנַֵם ֶְֶם /בְוֺךְ /22ְָר ֲבֵֵ ׅ/וֺן וׅר/ו/22ָ/SIָׅם:/PR

/HN/PR

/PR

May God console you among the mourners of Zion and
Jerusalem./PR

/PR

INTRODUCTION TO THE MOURNERSò KADDISH/PR

/PR

In reciting the Kaddish we affirm our awareness of holiness in
our world. Much of our experience of divine goodness, grace
and love has come to us through those whose lives have touched
our own. (Today we remember...) We invoke the transcendent
power of love and caring as we sanctify Godòs name./PR

Love is not changed by Death, and nothing is lost and all in the end is
harvest./PR

Edith Sitwell/PR

/PR

/SCN/XXOTE/XX. Congregations usually mention the names of congregants and their
relatives who have died in the previous week before reciting the Mournersò
Kaddish. In many congregations a /ITYahrzeit/XX list is read as well. In more
informal settings the leader sometimes invites those present to speak the
names of those they wish to be remembered.    /SC/XXD.A.T./XX/PR

/PR

